04240nam a22005175i 9780226610658DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802266106587 a10.7208/97802266106582doi  a(DE-B1597)523340  a(OCoLC)753480170  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aPHI0000002bisacsh  aAK 26600qHBZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/2573:1 aNye, Mary Jo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMichael Polanyi and His Generation :bOrigins of the Social Construction of Science /cMary Jo Nye. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b17 halftones, 2 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tONE. Scientific Culture in Europe and the Refugee Generation -- tTWO. Germany and Weimar Berlin as the City of Science -- tTHREE. Origins of a Social Perspective: Doing Physical Chemistry in Weimar Berlin -- tFOUR. Chemical Dynamics and Social Dynamics in Berlin and Manchester -- tFIVE. Liberalism and the Economic Foundations of the “Republic of Science” -- tSIX. Scientific Freedom and the Social Functions of Science -- tSEVEN. Political Foundations of the Philosophies of Science of Popper, Kuhn, and Polanyi -- tEIGHT. Personal Knowledge: Argument, Audiences, and Sociological Engagement -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Michael Polanyi and His Generation, Mary Jo Nye investigates the role that Michael Polanyi and several of his contemporaries played in the emergence of the social turn in the philosophy of science. This turn involved seeing science as a socially based enterprise that does not rely on empiricism and reason alone but on social communities, behavioral norms, and personal commitments. Nye argues that the roots of the social turn are to be found in the scientific culture and political events of Europe in the 1930s, when scientific intellectuals struggled to defend the universal status of scientific knowledge and to justify public support for science in an era of economic catastrophe, Stalinism and Fascism, and increased demands for applications of science to industry and social welfare. At the center of this struggle was Polanyi, who Nye contends was one of the first advocates of this new conception of science. Nye reconstructs Polanyi’s scientific and political milieus in Budapest, Berlin, and Manchester from the 1910s to the 1950s and explains how he and other natural scientists and social scientists of his generation—including J. D. Bernal, Ludwik Fleck, Karl Mannheim, and Robert K. Merton—and the next, such as Thomas Kuhn, forged a politically charged philosophy of science, one that newly emphasized the social construction of science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJewish scientistszGermanyxIntellectual life. 0aJewish scientistszHungaryxIntellectual life. 0aSciencexPhilosophyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSciencexSocial aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226610658423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226610658.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles